<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Texturedm1a2.png" class="image" title="1 = 3D model without textures2 = 3D model with textures"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/30/Texturedm1a2.png/180px-Texturedm1a2.png" width="180" height="132" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Texturedm1a2.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
1 = 3D model without textures<br />
2 = 3D model with textures</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Texture mapping</b> is a method for adding detail, surface texture, or colour to a <a href="/wiki/Computer-generated_imagery" title="Computer-generated imagery">computer-generated graphic</a> or <a href="/wiki/3D_model" title="3D model" class="mw-redirect">3D model</a>. Its application to 3D graphics was pioneered by Dr <a href="/wiki/Edwin_Catmull" title="Edwin Catmull">Edwin Catmull</a> in his Ph.D. thesis of 1974.</p>
